76561198025051194,Not Recommended,294370,13604378,"Posted: 25 December, 2014",all,emirfassad,"Not worth the time or money.  Extremely random with too few player choices and not enough information about the choices that are available.  The only rogue-like aspect to the game is permadeath.Maps are presnted as a hex grid  for no particular reason since map movement is point to point. Each of the several possible encounters can be met once & the player must make his choice without any suggestion of possible outcomes.  Few encounters well balanced.   Many cannot be avoided.    Once the player has exited a map he cannot return to it.  As a result, if the player encounters a situation which he cannot beat in his current condition there is rarely a way to improve the character and try again.Combat begins with players characters  deployed on a hed grid map, frequently with no opponents in view nor any suggestion of their location.  Nearly always surprised even though the text says that player is aware of opponents.  It is not uncommon for player's characters with seven or eight hit points each to face four or more opponents each with six to fifteen hit points, when played on easy.That the devs assume that placing the player into situations in which he has no chance of success makes for amusing game play is but one mark of their shortsightedness.Camping & inns do not replenish hit points and rewards for the rare battle victory are inadequate for character survival.There is no sense of progress.  No feeling of having learned how to increase the character's chance of success in subsequent games.The entire game could be condensed to having the player roll a die at the beginning and then declaring him failed or victorious.All in all a poorly designed game utterly lacking in the elements that that would make it enjoyable.The game is not difficult it is highly random with an extremely restrictive choice basis.  That means that the player's chance of completing each level is very small.The first level has eight to ten encounters.  Each encounter has two or three options.  Each option may have up to a half dozen outcomes.  Since each encounter occurs once per game sampling each of the possible  options on the first level  alone requires between 64 and 512 plays.It is relativly easy to reach the second map but highly unlikely that the play weill have gained enough knoweldge/experience from the first map to effect his chances of surviving to the third.The second map is a bit less random.  It has more combat encouters  but opponents are significantlhy stronger.  I place the probability of surviving any one combat between one-quarter and one-third call it 7/24.  There are four combat encounters, I believe.  The chance of surviving all of them would be about 1/140.  It takes 97 plays to have a 50% chance to complete this level.If you are willing to play the game a couple hundred times you might make it to the next map.Though there a many player choices on each map the outcome of each choice has a high variability.  That means that very little of the information you have garnered from previous game play will contribute to your choices in your current game.Since each map has few opportunities for character improvement unpassable roadblocks are common.It is these last two points where this game fails as a rogue-like.  The best rogue-like games present problems for the player and provide him with opportunities to surmount them.  The worst rogue-like games simple provide scads of random events.WazHack & Bionic Dues ae both good rogue-like games.  Crowntakers is not."
